Sepp Blatter headed FIFA for 17 years. AFP/Fabrice Coffrini JOHANNESBURG - The world football association has extended its ban on Former FIFA president Sepp Blatter and secretary general Jerome Valcke for a further six years and eight months. The ban has been imposed for multiple breaches of FIFA's ethics code and comes into force when their current suspension ends in October. READ: FIFA lodges criminal complaint against Blatter over museum Blatter and Valcke awarded themselves large bonuses in 2010. FIFA had already banned the two executives from all football-related activities after they were involved in a series of scandals in 2015. READ: Blatter says 'new facts' encourage him to fight ban They were also fined R16-million each. The 85-year-old was replaced by former UEFA general secretary Gianni Infantino in 2016.